Just in from CLEARWATER - "We are still planning on having our MS Cross Country Quad today at Clearwater. The forecast has pushed back the arrival of storms and rain to the point where we feel like we can run starting at 4:00 PM. We will be combining the 7th and 8th grade races in hopes of speeding up the meet and dodging any pending rain. Plan on the 7th grade 1 mile race starting at 4:00 PM and the 8th grade 2 mile race starting immediately following the conclusion of the 7th grade race. When you arrive, please check in at the finish line (south of our MS) to get your bibs. We will be hand timing the event, so I will email official results out this evening."

GO KNIGHTS! GO LADY KNIGHTS!

The WMS Knights and Lady Knights found lots of success Thursday in their Fall Season openers in football, volleyball, and girls tennis.

The 7A & 8A Football squads both came home from CIRCLE with WINS! The former 16-0, the latter 28-14.

The Volleyball squads won 3 of 4!

7A: Wellington WON 25-22, 25-17

8A: Wellington WON 25-15, 25-23

7B: Circle Won 25-20, 14-25, 15-11

8B: Wellington WON 26-24, 25-16

Last, but not least, the WMS 7/8 Girls Tennis squad dominated @ 9th St, hosting El Dorado and sweeping them as well. WMS winners were Kadynce Aufdengarten, Cruz Cornejo, Logan Robinson, Addie Hinshaw, Sawyer Parkey, Kira Worley, Jordyn Koehn and Adalyn Rains.

Great start - keep the good stuff coming!!

post_text: A note from our Elementary Counselors
shared_text:
Wellington Elementary Counselor's Corner
September 2 at 1:24 PM ·

Back to School is coming! We are excited to see you and your children back around the schools again!

We also acknowledge that this comes with some anxiety, worry, guilt, relief, confusion, and many other feelings for our wonderful parents!

Please know that teachers, administrators and staff are up at the schools working tirelessly to try to make things go as smoothly as possible as we start of on this new adventure together. Also know that your concerns and questions are always welcome here!

We don’t promise to have all the answers or always know the right thing to say or do. What we can promise is that we will walk through this with you and your students and work hard for you both.

As we start off on this new journey together, please check in with your kiddos, let us know how we can help and support you or your student(s), and check in with yourselves about what you are feeling during all of this change!

It’s going to be a great year in Wellington!

We don’t promise to have all the answers or always know the right thing to say or do. What we can promise is that we will walk through this with you and your students and work hard for you both.

post_text:
Jim McNiece, KSDE Board of Education Representative, attended last night’s USD 353 BOE meeting to present Washington Elementary with the Challenge Award. The Challenge Award recognizes schools for outstanding achievements and uncommon accomplishments based on Kansas math and reading assessment results and other qualifying factors, specifically the sample size, ethnicity and social-emotional status of those taking the test. Graduation rates for high schools and chronic absenteeism rates for middle and elementary schools are also factored in. The top 100 Kansas schools are selected for this honor each year.
Congratulations Washington Elementary administrators, teachers, staff and students!!

Reminder! Tomorrow is enrollment and Visa card pick up day from 12-7pm at your student(s) school. We want to take a minute to explain further the Back to School Commitment Form. Parents/Guardians will be choosing whether they are sending their students to school on-site or remote. Below is information explaining each learning model and expectations. We encourage you to read this to make an informed decision for your student(s). We are aware that there are still many questions. We are currently working on details and the continued draft of the reopening plan will be presented to the BOE on Aug. 10th for approval. We know that things change rapidly and everyone’s comfort levels are going to be different. We will work with families as needs change.
The complete list of what you need to bring is online on the USD 353 website.

FOR IMMEDIATE RELEASE

July 28, 2020

KSHSAA Fall Activities Permitted to Begin As Scheduled

TOPEKA, Kan. - By action of the KSHSAA Executive Board Tuesday, all fall activities will begin as scheduled for the 2020-21 school year. This includes practice and competition.

Local school districts retain the right to modify the start dates for practice or competition based on their local and county health recommendations.

The KSHSAA considerations for fall activities released on July 22 are still in effect. Those considerations are posted here:

RETURN TO ACTIVITY - GENERAL CONSIDERATIONS

Kansas State High School Activities Association
July 15 at 5:40 PM ·

The KSHSAA believes participation in school and school activities is critical for the students of Kansas and we strive to provide those opportunities for students this fall. This Friday (7/17) the KSHSAA had planned to distribute considerations and guidance for all fall activities to take place starting August 17. With the announcement today (7/15) from Governor Kelly, we will not release any information Friday. Rather we will go back and look at models and plans that are in place with a delayed start and release information when appropriate.
text:
Kansas State High School Activities Association
July 15 at 5:40 PM ·

The KSHSAA believes participation in school and school activities is critical for the students of Kansas and we strive to provide those opportunities for students this fall. This Friday (7/17) the KSHSAA had planned to distribute considerations and guidance for all fall activities to take place starting August 17. With the announcement today (7/15) from Governor Kelly, we will not release any information Friday. Rather we will go back and look at models and plans that are in place with a delayed start and release information when appropriate.

post_text:
KSHSAA Statement on masks/face coverings...

Considerations for Masks/Face Coverings

July 2, 2020
Based on Governor Kelly’s Executive Order 20-52 (released July 2, 2020), and unless specific guidance within your county indicates otherwise, masks or other face coverings should be worn by participants in any organized sports activity anytime participants are around others and unable to maintain 6-foot
physical distancing.

Per CDC guidelines, individuals who are engaged in high intensity activities, like running, may not be able to wear a mask or face covering if it causes difficulty breathing. Additionally, masks should not be worn during activities that cause the mask to become wet.

The KSHSAA encourages coaches to consider alternative activities if adequate physical distancing cannot be maintained in the absence of the participant wearing a mask. All non-participants in workout activities such as coaches, staff and non-participating students should wear a mask or face covering at all times when around others and 6-foot physical distancing cannot be maintained.

UPDATE with the 2020 Summer Weights & Conditioning Program.

post_text:
As we wrap up the 2019-2020 school year, we want to take a moment again to say thank you. Thank you teachers, students, parents, administrators and staff for coming together these last nine weeks for continuous learning. It was a journey filled with many emotions and even more “mute your mics.” We were inspired by our teachers and staff’s dedication and mourned with our Seniors. We held virtual art and baking classes, spirit week, and show and tells. We completed projects, papers, assignments and physical activity challenges. We found creative ways to teach, learn, and stay engaged. Together, we rose to the challenge. Have an amazing summer!
#proudtobe353
#crusaderstrong

post_text: Congrats to STATE ESSAY WINNER, WHS Freshman Taylon Ellis!
shared_text:
Steven Sturgis
May 22 at 12:54 PM ·

I really enjoy sharing these kinds of posts. WHS had a "FRESHMAN" enter an essay contest put on by the KANSAS BUSINESS HALL of FAME (KBHF). There were 98 entries from across the State. The "3" Top Winners State-Wide were:

*Shea Inlow - Sophomore from Sedgwick HS
*Emma Elder - Senior from Nemaha Central HS

and drum roll please.............

*Taylon Ellis - FRESHMAN from Wellington HS!!!!!!!!

All "3" will be honored at an event that honors the Kansas Exporter of the Year, Governor's Award for Excellence, and other awards, tentatively scheduled for June 18th in Topeka. The TOP 3 (Taylon, Shea & Emma) also received $200 checks!!

Great Job Mr. Ellis!! (I had the pleasure sitting next to Taylon for a while at a Wrestling Tournament here this past winter)...to keep it short and sweet, a fine and impressive young man and very enjoyable to talk to. I'm not surprised his essay was TOP NOTCH!! GREAT JOB CRUSADER!! Way to represent, and only a Freshman!! WOW!!

Courtesy Photo / Mrs. Case @ WHS

post_text:
Congratulations to WHS Senior Austin Soles. Austin signed, in a curbside ceremony at Travelin' Smoke BBQ Saturday afternoon, to play basketball this coming school year at Southwestern College in Winfield.Southwestern is part of the National Association of Intercollegiate Athletics (NAIA), and are in the Kansas Collegiate Athletic Conference (KCAC).

Present for the signing, were Austin's WHS Coaches, multiple family and friends.

Pictured are Austin with his parents Billy and Traci Soles. Also pictured with his coaches L to R, Rick Roitman, Joe Newman, and Matthew Metcalf. Two of Austin's teammates and pals, were present as well, L to R, next year Senior Tanner Meyer and this year Senior Zane Cornejo.

We are proud of you Austin - keep up the hustle and great attitude! GOOD LUCK MOUNDBUILDER!

shared_text:
Steven Sturgis
March 26 at 11:27 AM ·

The Sumner Co. Health Department received official confirmation very late Wednesday night of a positive COVID-19 case in Sumner County. The patient is a man in his 60's who resides in the northern part of the county. He is currently hospitalized in SG County. The Health Dept. has started their disease investigation and locating contacts of the patient.

To help protect yourself, they remind everyone to:
-continue to practice social distancing
-avoid close contact with others
-avoid touching eyes, nose and mouth with unwashed hands
-wash your hands often with soap and water for at least 20 secs.
-use alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol

The Sumner County Health Department will make a scheduled statement when they have any further information they can share.

-use alcohol-based hand sanitizer that contains at least 60% alcohol

The Sumner County Health Department will make a scheduled statement when they have any further information they can share.

Wellington Public Schools is providing FREE pre-packaged meals.

Kansas State Department of Education
March 17 at 9:01 AM ·

The Continuous Learning Task Force worked throughout the night on a comprehensive plan for delivering education to students while school buildings remain closed. The task force anticipates having a draft of this plan finalized by the end of the day Wednesday, March 18.

We can’t emphasize enough that this is a herculean effort being led by our Kansas teachers. We thank this group - and every teacher in Kansas - for all they’re doing to ensure that learning continues for our students.

Please lend them your support, and trust that they are working to provide the very best opportunities for our students during this time of uncertainty.

EDIT March 17 4:25 p.m. - The list of educators on the Continuous Learning Task Force is available here: https://www.ksde.org/Home/Quick-Links/News-Room/commissioner-watson-convenes-continuous-learning-task-force-1

post_text: It was space day for USD 353 third graders! All third grade students in the district just completed a space unit in their classrooms and met today for some space related projects. They made LEGO spaceships, gazed at stars, and designed space colonies. There was even a NASA space station and moon landing station. The astronauts examined articles found on the moon and sent important data back to NASA via video chat.

Celebrating 100 years at WHS
1920-2020
We invite you to share in 100 years of education at Wellington High School as we celebrate the past and look forward to the future!

Date: Saturday, May 2nd
Time: 11am-3pm Come and Go
Place: Wellington High School

Join us for:
-Cookies
-WHS memorabilia displays
-Tour maps of all WHS past locations
-Door prizes donated by local businesses
-Commemorative item giveaway (while supplies last!)
-Video highlights of WHS through the decades
-Digital yearbooks
-Photobooth

This event is free of charge and open to past and present WHS
students, teachers, administrators, BOE members, staff and families. Grab your classmates or colleagues and come reminisce! More details will be available later as plans continue. In the meantime, please help us spread the word.

It is not required to RSVP to attend, but we would love to know if you are coming in order to help us plan! Please RSVP with your name and number of people attending to WHS100@usd353.com

post_text: On Monday, USD 353 teachers engaged in a professional development opportunity focusing on educating students, families and entire communities on poverty. Rebecca Lewis-Pankratz, a learning consultant with ESSDACK, guided participants through a poverty simulation. She also spoke about her personal struggle with poverty and addiction and shared her passion for trauma-informed schools along with finding resolutions to student poverty. Rebecca shared insights on how to help all people find the tools necessary to turn kids from at-risk to at-promise. It was an impactful day as our teachers worked to equip themselves with new knowledge, awareness and skills.

text: Today’s PSA brought to you by Washington Elementary:

post_text:
Wellington High School Blood Drive

Sponsored by our National Honor Society chapter and American Red Cross

Friday, February 28th
9:00am-2:30pm
WHS Auxiliary Gym

Chances are you or someone you know has a personal connection to cancer. You might not be able to change a cancer diagnosis but you can help those fighting cancer by teaming up with Wellington High School students to fight the critical blood shortage! Currently, there is less than a three-day supply of both O negative and O positive blood products. In order to rebuild our blood supply, we need blood donors of all blood types to help fill the blood drive schedule. Right now we still have 42 appointments available. Will you help us support patients in need?

To view available times and to schedule your life saving donation appointment please Visit redcrossblood.org use Keyword: WellingtonHigh or download the American Red Cross donor app or contact me at hrausch@usd353.com.

Donors must be 16(+) years or older. 16 year-old donors need a signed parental consent form.

Photo ID or Red Cross Donor Card required at time of donation.

post_text: Washington Elementary Principal Ann Shinliver and teachers Liz Aguilar, Jayme Lowe and Gina Schnelle presented at the BOE monthly meeting last night about all of the great things happening at Washington Elementary. They specifically spoke about how they implement the Multi-Tier System of Supports and Alignment (MTSS) system. MTSS is a system of prevention, early intervention, and support to ensure all students are learning from instruction. They spoke about the successes and major gains Washington students are having using the MTSS system. Thank you to these amazing educators and the entire Washington staff!

It was an emotional character education assembly today at Eisenhower as they celebrated the character trait of integrity AND honored some very special guests. Eisenhower secretary Cortney Peninger has been out as she battles cancer and recovers from surgery. There were BIG smiles today as Mrs. Cortney returned to be honored at the assembly and help hand out student of the month certificates. In addition to honoring Mrs. Cortney, Ike students invited cancer survivors and fighters to form their fan tunnel.
These amazing kiddos made a video for Mrs. Cortney telling her how special she is to them and ended the assembly by singing Martina McBrides song “I’m gonna love you through it.”
Congrats to the Ike students of the month! Along with her Eisenhower family, all of us at USD 353 wish Mrs. Cortney the best and can’t wait to see her back behind her desk SOON!

post_text:
The Eisenhower 3rd graders paid visits today to the KWHS NEWS Studio at WHS to learn a few basics about lighting, about sound, and about the green screen. We took pictures and videos of the groups while they were there and told them we'd edit those together after they left and the let the world and them see how our day at KWHS went.

The students learned about the power of music and other background sounds and effects, all valuable tools, amongst many tools, a film editor can use to put it all together in the end, in a way hopefully found pleasing by those who view it.

These were sharp kids - they asked a lot of very good questions, and they seemed to be having fun on their outing. In addition to the visit to KWHS Studio, the 3 groups also visited SUSAN'S PORTRAITS and also visited the WMS RADIO GROUP.

Steven Sturgis
January 23, 2017 at 6:23 AM ·

This year's DUKE CANDIDATES were announced Friday out at WHS - congratulations to Connor Burnett, Brock Edwards, Matthew Mason, Noah Rinehart and Lukas Soria! 2 of the 5 were out of town on Friday so will get a group pic of the 5 early this week. Closer to the coronation we will also be posting FORMAL PICS of the candidates on the DISTRICT & CRUSADER WEBSITES!! Congrats again to all "5" - awesome group and now part of a tradition that has lived on here at WHS for many decades - read on!!

THE HISTORY OF OUR WHS DUKE!

The 1st WHS Duke was crowned at the Basketball Bounce on March 15, 1948! His name was Neel Goodrum. Other candidates included Charles Tibbs, Eddie Howell, Gordon Goodrum and Joe Smith. The MEGAPHONE (yearbook) sponsor at the time, a Ms. Helen Mills, was quoted saying at the first crowning, "We hope the Duke of Wellington will become a lasting tradition and a pleasant memory of high school life..." Well Ms. Mills, the 70th DUKE of WELLINGTON will be crowned in less than 2 weeks - your hope in 1948 lives on in 2017 at the HOME OF THE CRUSADERS - WHS!

shared_text:
Steven Sturgis
January 15 at 1:15 PM ·

A little more history about one of our schools...how many of you knew (I didn't until I ran across this architectural drawing), that the original plans (or at least the plans at some point perhaps) for the then new high school at 605 North A, (present middle school) built in the late 50's / early 60's were twice as large as what eventually was built. Only the left half (or so) of this drawing was actually constructed, the two pods that are there now weren't added for almost 10 years after the original build. (1970). When the pods were added, that also included the addition of the cafeteria. Prior to that, all schools had an open lunch hour (and it was for an hour), many students would go downtown to eat at Glasco Drug or Chief Drug (and other places) or of course Dick's Drive In, A & W or home for lunch. In middle school, prior to changeover to a closed lunch hour, I remember walking downtown and eating lunch with my dad who's insurance office was next to Glasco Drug. Good times.

January 12 at 6:37 AM ·

HAPPY 100th BIRTHDAY WELLINGTON HIGH SCHOOL!!

In the FALL of 1920, Sumner County HS closed, and in its place, Wellington High School began. WHS was housed in the same building until 1929 when students were moved to the new 3 story structure at 8th and A Streets. That would be the home of the Crusaders until the early 60's, when 2 blocks north the 3rd HS came to be (to accommodate baby boomers from WWII) and the Classes of 1962 thru 2004 called it their Crusader Home. (The picture below was taken in 1970 after the "pods" had been added.) The 2020 graduating class this year will be the 16th class to graduate from the present facility located on E. 16th. The WHS Class of 2020 will also be the "100th WHS Graduating Class"...

HAPPY CENTENNIAL BIRTHDAY WELLINGTON HIGH SCHOOL!! Many great memories for many people. GO BIG RED!!

Staff members at WMS present students with cards when they are exhibiting good behavior or are caught doing something kind. The card is cashed in for candy or a pencil and their name is placed on the 100’s chart for a chance to win the grand prize. When all 100 spaces are filled a grand prize winner is drawn.
Congrats Dusty! It pays to be a polite Knight!

post_text:
The Wellington FFA Chapter took more eggs to the Wellington Food Bank on Friday before the holidays. The Chapter has donated 22 dozen eggs this fall. The chickens the chapter is raising have begun production and will continue well into 2020. Students are cleaning and grading eggs before they go to the food bank. Eggs have also been donated to the High School and are being used by the kitchen staff in preparing meals for students.
This summer the Wellington FFA Officers attended the State Conference for Chapter Leaders (SCCL) where along with over 200 other FFA Officers they packed over 5000 bags of macaroni and cheese dinners. Today the FFA took four cases (144 bags) of meals that they packed to the food bank so families could enjoy them over the holidays and into next year. The Wellington FFA Chapter wishes everyone in Wellington and the surrounding areas a Merry Christmas and a Happy New Year!

Congratulations to the WMS 7th Grade Lady Knight Basketball Team - this school year's PATRIOT LEAGUE GIRLS BASKETBALL CHAMPIONS!!! The Lady Knights and their coach Ashlyn Whaley, defeated Prairie Hills Tuesday evening at Clearwater to claim the title! Final score was WMS 51 Prairie Hills 41 – great job Lady Knights – congrats on a great season, a season that ended with 14 wins and just 1 loss. Ironically, that 1 loss was to Prairie Hills back on December 9th. The Lady Knights won the one that mattered most!
CONGRATS PLAYERS! CONGRATS COACH WHALEY!

post_text: Eisenhower 3rd Grade welcomed members of the WHS Debate Team to their classroom on Thursday. Students are preparing to debate whether Julius Caesar was a hero or a traitor, but before their classroom debate, they needed to learn from the experts! Under the guidance of Kim Harriger, team members debated whether dog is truly man’s best friend. Ultimately, they sided with the affirmative! Thank you WHS debate for coming to demonstrate the ins and outs of a proper debate.

Sr. Spotlight!
Brittney Bentz, a WHS Sr., has been named a Semi-Finalist in the Distinguished Scholarship Invitational (DSI) at Wichita State University. DSI is a $64,000 scholarship awarded to three incoming freshmen that plan to attend WSU. Brittney is one of 82 semi-finalists that made the cut from a field of 656 students. She wrote two essays, went to the WSU campus for an interview and participated in a team-building exercise with other scholarship contestants. Congrats, Brittney!

post_text:
The WHS Choir presented "WELCOME CHRISTMAS" at their holiday concert on Thursday, Dec. 5th. Choir Director Jennifer Ault, on maternity leave would have been proud of her students.

Guest Director (Band) Allen Hisken filled in with Carol Hisken on piano, and together the group performed such classics as "White Christmas", "The Little Drummer Boy", "Carol of the Bells", "The First Noel" and "Holy Night".

Individual performances by Brenna Brown, Michaela Adkins, Braeden Bevan, Liz Reitz, Alexis Hearlson, Abigail White, Mason Lough, Hunter Lough and Britteny Bentz were all superb.

WHS has very talented stage performers - awesome experience to watch and listen to.

MORE PICS @ www.usd353.com!
